    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "To try and help move this conversation along, what are some of the actions we expect people to be able to do on long press for a chat (and we have to consider DApps)? Some things that come to mind: \r\n- Delete\r\n- Mark as unread\r\n- Pin (particularly helpful for group chat?) \r\n- Ignore / Block\r\n- Mute / turn notifications off\r\n- ...?\r\n\r\nAll of which are useful but have not heard that any of these things are particularly necessary or painful atm other than 'Delete' which has been covered in this issue. Both are learned behaviors as is and, unfortunately, splintered across different platforms. Could we implement the swipe gesture as @errorists has outlined above - i.e. 60 points + final confirmation - with a principle that we use it for destructive actions (more context: https://www.nngroup.com/articles/contextual-swipe/)? And a plan to follow up with long press in the future for some of these key actions. Wdyt? \n\n<blockquote><img src=\"https://media.nngroup.com/media/articles/opengraph_images/Slide057.png\" width=\"48\" align=\"right\"><div>Nielsen Norman Group</div><div><strong><a href=\"https://www.nngroup.com/articles/contextual-swipe/\">Using Swipe to Trigger Contextual Actions</a></strong></div><div>Implementations of swipe-to-delete or swipe to reveal contextual actions often suffer from usability problems.</div></blockquote>",
